 29-year-old criticises UCI for track and road ‘segregation’<br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/jan/08/bradley-wiggins-new-team-sky\" title=\"\">• Bradley Wiggins unveils new team to be sponsored by Sky</a>","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>Mark Cavendish has indicated he is unlikely to race at the 2016 Olympics in Rio de Janeiro. The 29-year-old, who missed out on medals at both the 2008 and 2012 Olympics in Beijing and London, told BBC Sport his obligations with the Etixx-Quick Step road racing team are likely to prevent him from being in the shape required to qualify for Great Britain’s team.</p> <p>“It’s not 100% I’m not doing the Olympics but it’s difficult,” he said. “It probably won’t happen, if I’m honest. I’ve got a road job.”</p> <p>Cavendish, who is entering the final year of his contract with the Belgian team he joined from Team Sky in 2013, has long said his commitment to his employers had to come before his Olympic ambitions.</p> <p>Adding to his uncertainty over Rio is his recognition that the road race course may not suit a sprinter, given that it includes three laps over a lengthy climb as well as a cobblestone section, while he does not have the time to dedicate to track cycling.</p> <p>“The [course for the] road race doesn’t suit me,” Cavendish said. “The time trial, well, I’m not a time triallist. And as for the track, the UCI has segregated track and road cycling completely.”</p> <p>Earlier on Thursday,<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/jan/08/bradley-wiggins-new-team-sky\" title=\"\"> Sir Bradley Wiggins confirmed plans to launch a new cycling team</a> when his Sky contract expires in April, which will race at the continental level while following a programme designed to allow the riders involved – Wiggins included – to get in shape for the track races in Rio.</p> <p>Cavendish, who competed alongside Wiggins in the Madison in Beijing, believes that is a reflection of the changes that no longer make it possible for cyclists to perform at elite levels on both the road and the track.</p> <p>“You have to do what Sir Bradley Wiggins is doing and quit road cycling to be able to qualify for it,” he said. “It’s killing track cycling, because you never get the road stars doing track anymore. Track cycling is going to die, particularly on the endurance side. As a British athlete I want to do the Olympics but it’s hard. I can’t do it on the road, can’t do it in the time trial and on the track there’s just no way to qualify without quitting the road.”</p>","headline":"Mark Cavendish likely to miss Rio 2016 Olympics due to road commitments","trailText":"Mark Cavendish has indicated he is unlikely to race at the 2016 Olympics in Rio de Janeiro and criticised the UCI for ‘segregating’ track and road cycling","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/pictures/2015/1/8/1420752129285/Mark-Cavendish-006.jpg","wordcount":"385","commentable":"false","byline":"Press Association","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2015-01-11T21:25:23Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/jan/08/mark-cavendish-rio-2016-olympics-track-road-cycling","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2015/jan/08/mark-cavendish-rio-2016-olympics-track-road-cycling","tags":[{"id":"sport/markcavendish","webTitle":"Mark Cavendish","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/markcavendish","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/markcavendish","references":[]},{"id":"sport/olympic-games-2016","webTitle":"Olympic Games 2016","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/olympic-games-2016","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/olympic-games-2016","references":[]},{"id":"sport/olympic-games","webTitle":"Olympic Games","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/olympic-game