full time, I looked for Brown to see his reaction: luckily he leapt high and punched the air. What pleases me about this picture is that he did it in a way that meant I had other players in the background, giving it a far better context</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"314da8b805e701560cf5074f618e8b0b16776e69\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865369411/fb806da6-186f-4b79-9184-57432f5dd678-320x480.jpeg\" alt=\"Manu Tuilagi, Leicester Tigers training ground, Oadby. 26/3/14.\" width=\"320\" height=\"480\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Manu Tuilagi, Leicester Tigers training ground, Oadby. 26/3/14</strong><br>70mm lens, 1/125 f4.5, ISO 400.<br>Having been there before I knew the football club Leicester use for media work was a pretty uninspiring place to take a portrait. I set up a situation in one of the dressing rooms where I could put a light on the roof shining straight down. I wanted Manu to look up to the light and point in a way I had previously seen him celebrate a try for England. He is also a deeply religious man and this pose along with those distinctive tattoos made the image I was after</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"1daae139cadcac872ce782d6e8b11327879016fe\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865335174/6a783e39-6085-46ca-801f-dfee00f51c9d-620x402.jpeg\" alt=\"Grand National, Aintree. 5/4/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"402\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Grand National, Aintree. 5/4/14</strong><br>24mm lens, 1/2000 f5.6, ISO 1600.<br>The ‘nations favourite race’ is always one of my highlights of the year. I have a plan that I have worked on for many years that enables me to cover as much of the race as possible. Part of this strategy is placing a remote camera low down by the inside of the notorious Chair fence, the biggest jump on the course. Some years there are no fallers, however this year it came up trumps as pre-race favourite Teaforthree ploughed through the fir and came down much to the disappointment of many punters around the country </span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"2b39fd1b7bf68e1bae7be1cd0746b5bf497c5dcf\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865964252/80beb011-6688-4ac7-9ead-cf53a50b1f7d-620x400.jpeg\" alt=\"Jose Mourinho, Liverpool v Chelsea Premier League match, Anfield. 27/4/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"400\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>José Mourinho, Liverpool v Chelsea, Premier League, Anfield. 27/4/14</strong><br>400mm lens, 1/1250 f4, ISO 500.<br>I really love Mourinho. Over the years he has provided so much entertainment on the touchline for photographers. This was the crucial match towards the end of the season, Liverpool needed the victory to keep their title challenge on course. This image illustrates his delaying tactics as he refuses to give the ball back to Steven Gerrard. José’s plan worked to perfection, Chelsea won 2-0 and Liverpool’s long-held dream of the title had been stolen from their grasp</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"db1c570ea6b8113050aab070cee64aae0dfb36d1\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865398291/8aa2a199-6ed4-4fe7-8f1d-ae1d9b626b38-620x392.jpeg\" alt=\"World Series diving, London Aquatics Centre, Stratford. 25/4/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"392\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>World Series diving, London Aquatics Centre, Stratford. 25/4/14</strong><br>140mm lens, 1/4000 f2.8, ISO 400.<br>This was the first professional competition to be held at the London Aquatics Centre since the Olympics. The arena was so different from how I remembered it; when the Olympics were held no natural light was allowed in. The television companies running the games are always seeking controlled arenas where the light is constantly the same, so any windows or potential sources of daylight were boarded up. It was refreshing to be able to use the big windows again as a graphic backdrop to the action. </span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"6756e1ce8f4c4ecdab294b98b4d5fed5e531bb0f\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865472718/9f8def88-da83-452d-b130-89495f0b24c5-620x412.jpeg\" alt=\"England v Peru, World cup warm-up match, Wembley. 30/5/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"412\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>England v Peru, international friendly, Wembley. 30/5/14</strong><br>500mm lens, 1/1000 f4, ISO 3200.<br>This was a very humdrum match that was slowly meandering to its conclusion. All through the game fans had amused themselves by making paper planes and attempting to throw them and reach the pitch. Eventually one perfect design made it all the way from the top deck giving poor Hansell Riojas of Peru an unexpected shock as it tapped him on the shoulder. Without doubt the highlight of the night for me and most of the crowd </span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"379bfe85f7b1dc03b16ef65e703eae97a7231431\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419866044849/d63871fc-a33b-4ed7-ac6c-1f14b5ec2c50-620x418.jpeg\" alt=\"Luis Suarez advert, Copacabana Beach, Brazil 25/6/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"418\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Luis Suárez advert, Copacabana Beach, Brazil. 25/6/14</strong><br>50mm lens, 1/200 f2.8, ISO 1250.<br>It was the day after the infamous Suarez bite in the Uruguay v Italy match. So when the biting controversy engulfed the World Cup I headed back to this advert to see if I could make a decent frame. I wasn’t disappointed: it was great fun to see fans from all over the world posing in differing ways. I shot the pictures and filed them quickly. The response I got online to that simple gallery was amazing. It was even trending on Twitter in Paris – how bizarre! </span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"d286994b3953c80458aac6e1096c87cd975c9f9a\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865423421/ef4d3e43-310d-4c5c-aa2f-af904d3b7e24-620x398.jpeg\" alt=\"Novak Djokovic, men’s singles final, Wimbledon. 6/7/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"398\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Novak Djokovic, men’s singles final, Wimbledon. 6/7/14</strong><br>145mm lens, 1/1600 f4.5, ISO 400.<br>To be photographing the men’s singles final on a beautiful sunlit afternoon at Wimbledon is something special. As the photo areas by the side of the court are dug into the ground, it gives us a fantastic low angle which, combined with a lovely shaded background, makes for wonderful pictures. So, when Djokovic dived to make a volley late in the match on my side of the net, all the factors came together. It showed perfectly how determined the Serb was to retain his title with victory over Roger Federer</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"da1f386775143618867db3ebe18f0300c28a3bc6\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865680254/eb34dca8-6a7e-4056-bc06-9c5fa0c83ab7-620x395.jpeg\" alt=\"Womens 10k scratch race, Commonwealth Games, Sir Chris Hoy velodrome, Glasgow. 26/7/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"395\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Womens 10k scratch race, Commonwealth Games, Sir Chris Hoy Velodrome, Glasgow. 26/7/14</strong><br>33mm lens, 1/8 f8, ISO 100.<br>I noticed that the lighting in this arena was patchy with a couple of bright hotspots. It reflected off the track in a way that by shooting from the inside to the out you could almost silhouette the riders flying by. By deliberately overexposing I could make the track look white. The black-clad New Zealanders breaking from the pack made it easier to get a decent contrast. The blurred effect is achieved by panning with the riders and zooming out the lens at the same time</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"0e1cf2eac89530466a15623b3d515e03401ca606\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865789628/5163b00e-3641-432f-b528-0745d657ed83-620x388.jpeg\" alt=\"Mens singles squash final, Commonwealth Games, Scotstoun Sports campus, Glasgow. 28/7/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"388\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Men’s singles squash final, Commonwealth Games, Scotstoun Sports campus, Glasgow. 28/7/14</strong><br>44mm lens, 1/1600 f3.5, ISO 5000.<br>The day before the final I asked for a position right ‘by the tin’ shooting low down through the glass wall. As the final went on, I shifted position from the forehand side to the backhand. I realised that by putting my lens right up against a glass supporting strut in front of me I could achieve an amazing reflection. All I had to do was keep the camera in the precise position and wait for the action to occur in exactly the right spot. It took ages but it was worth it</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"6e71947e7984e7cc588e59e1774dd00b9d7d1b05\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865617578/d4c23804-4359-416b-a5a2-c208d0ac9d47-620x395.jpeg\" alt=\"Mens team gymnastics final, Commonwealth Games, SSC Hydro, Glasgow. 29/7/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"395\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Men’s team gymnastics final, Commonwealth Games, SSC Hydro, Glasgow. 29/7/14</strong><br>33mm lens, 1/2000 f4.5, ISO 3200.<br>Occasionally I use a bit of camera trickery to spice up a picture, in this case a multiple exposure. I do this very rarely as I believe you have to use it like a novelty – do it all the time and it becomes boring. With this example I wanted the movement in two gymnasts at the same time to show different aspects of the sport and give more interest. A tip I have learnt from doing multiple exposures is not to use a fast motor-drive as you want the action to be spread out over the frame</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"4ea81f93c02cdc29515139775cb5bb5a5f1fe836\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865501813/dc41ac97-640d-4f71-a908-3a15fc88d12c-620x380.jpeg\" alt=\"Mens Heavyweight boxing, Commonwealth Games, SECC, Glasgow. 30/7/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"380\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Men’s heavyweight boxing, Commonwealth Games, SECC, Glasgow. 30/7/14</strong><br>500mm lens, 1/2000 f4, ISO 5000.<br>It was the first time I had seen amateur boxing without head guards. I was sent to illustrate how the style of fighting was changing because of the lack of protection and how more cuts were occurring. In the men’s heavyweight quarter-finals Samir El-Mais of Canada got a particularly nasty injury while fighting Warren Baister of England, thus providing the perfect image for the story. El-Mais carried on and won the contest despite having blood right in his eye</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"c94f57fd4d83c6fe69728df9b9a76656fcfbe392\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865746204/19caa484-b012-4420-87b8-0ae8f4cfd4b9-620x411.jpeg\" alt=\"Mens 10,000m final, Commonwealth Games, Hampden Park, Glasgow. 1/8/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"411\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Men’s 10,000m final, Commonwealth Games, Hampden Park, Glasgow. 1/8/1</strong>4<br>70mm lens, 1/2000 f5, ISO 200.<br>The Friday evening at the athletics turned out to be beautiful and sunny so I had to make the most of it. For a couple of hours I was working on angles around the stadium to find the best spots to shoot the lengthening shadows. Luckily the 10,000m final was at exactly the right time. It was just a case of going to the position I had worked out previously and getting the exposure right. The light was only perfect like this for a few laps before the sun disappeared behind the back of the stands</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"ac8edee315dece463201c49a2e878310f806f8ca\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865817801/779312b5-1017-42cf-800e-6f4b18bd0161-620x412.jpeg\" alt=\"Carl Frampton, IBF World Super bantamweight title fight, Titanic Slipways, Belfast. 6/9/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"412\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Carl Frampton, IBF World Super bantamweight title fight, Titanic Slipways, Belfast. 6/9/14</strong><br>25mm lens, 1/500 f3.2, ISO 4000.<br>This was an amazing moment for me. I have followed Frampton since his early days as a professional; his story, along with his manager Barry McGuigan, fascinates me. The decision to hold this fight with Kiko Martínez outdoors on the slipway where the Titanic was built, was a risky one. Fortunately the night was dry and cloudless. As Frampton emerged in all white he looked up to the moonlit sky, the united fans of Belfast bellowing their support. It gave me goose-bumps</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"3f4175b31d3c08ac555f752fcc525c38da843ff1\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865893360/7a43d57a-8103-4ff0-91af-edfaccab5de9-620x411.jpeg\" alt=\"Invictus Games, Lee Valley athletics centre. 11/9/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"411\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Michael Kacer, Invictus Games, Lee Valley Athletics Centre. 11/9/14</strong><br>102mm lens, 1/1600 f2.8, ISO 500.<br>When I headed off to the first day of competition in the inaugural Invictus Games I wasn’t sure quite what to make of it. But when I saw this veteran with one arm missing, scar down the side of his face and distinctive contact lenses, I knew I could get a striking image. Lying down behind the shot put circle to get a clean background, I made sure I had the lens wide open to throw all the focus onto that amazing, determined face</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"c545656fb7ff5961adc4ef1855cd8c3f79583fbe\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865447532/cec19949-4875-462b-9381-89f200a6a755-620x396.jpeg\" alt=\"Ian Poulter, Ryder Cup, Gleneagles. 26/9/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"396\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Ian Poulter, Ryder Cup, Gleneagles. 26/9/14</strong><br>300mm lens, 1/1600 f4, ISO 400.<br>In a press conference just before the start of the Ryder Cup, Poulter had given himself the nickname ‘The Postman’ because “he always delivers”. It was a very brash move, even though he had a terrific record in previous matches. However, nothing at Gleneagles was going to plan for him until this moment on the Saturday, when in his fourball match alongside Rory McIlroy he holed a huge chip from off the green at the 15th. Luckily I was close by as he celebrated and the self-inflicted pressure seeming to burst out of him </span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"493ec939d1b052c6f76d1455ed532bb209a3387d\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865712569/be7e63d1-62c4-4da5-ab57-b73f63fd3b7a-620x416.jpeg\" alt=\"Rory McIlroy, Ryder Cup, Gleneagles. 28/9/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"416\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Rory McIlroy, Ryder Cup, Gleneagles. 28/9/14</strong><br>24mm lens, 1/3200 f5, ISO 800.<br>This is not the sort of sports picture that I normally like: i.e. a sportsman looking straight down my lens celebrating. Europe had won the Ryder Cup again, it was a bit chaotic as jubilant golfers cavorted on the 15th green, champagne and camera gear was flying everywhere. I decided to exit from the scrum surrounding captain Paul McGinley in order to find the undoubted star of the year. I tracked him down and he did this for me. It’s his almost youthful expression that really works and why I like this frame so much</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"6bfc189f4401c61db0d9afcd942426564f113ca7\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865930157/347d71b5-5180-40dd-93ea-7eaef6cdcadc-620x407.jpeg\" alt=\"Galatasaray fans, v Arsenal in the Champions League, Emirates Stadium. 1/10/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"407\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Galatasaray v Arsenal. Champions League, Emirates Stadium. 1/10/14</strong><br>200mm lens, 1/3200 f3.5, ISO 1000.<br>One of the most memorable matches I ever covered was the infamous ‘Welcome to Hell’ game in Istanbul in November 1993 between Galatasaray and Manchester United; that night the terraces were permanently on fire with flares. Approaching this game I kept in the back of my mind the pyrotechnic tendencies of the Turkish fans. A feisty challenge in the first half ignited the atmosphere just behind me so it was simply a case of moving to where I could silhouette a particular fan to create this image</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"b75e9a26b1fc447701d6bdeb68540c4d94d3dec4\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865558520/950f24af-0d0c-45fe-a534-3d4f6830ff7a-620x404.jpeg\" alt=\"Zlatan Ibrahimovic, Paris. 3/10/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"404\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>Zlatan Ibrahimovic, Paris. 3/10/14.</strong><br>70mm lens, 1/200 f 4.5, ISO 400 <br>I had a few hours at the PSG training ground to get my lighting right in a lovely timber-lined room. I was all ready and prepared to do various poses around the location. Then Zlatan walked in with a press officer in tow, who said “you’ve got a couple of minutes and you can’t show his feet.” Plans straight out the window! I think I managed to push it to five minutes with the press officer yapping constantly in my ear. It was such a pity as I think Zlatan was just starting to warm up and would have been quite happy to do more</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"71d02b7d04fb044ba7bc6a669c74bca738dd4f62\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/29/1419865529266/2465c4ac-bdf7-4c0e-b22b-5b2dee56f016-620x410.jpeg\" alt=\"England v New Zealand, Autumn international, Twickenham. 8/11/14.\" width=\"620\" height=\"410\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><strong>England v New Zealand, Autumn international, Twickenham. 8/11/14</strong><br>125mm lens, 1/1600 f5.6, ISO 4000.<br>Twickenham unveiled its new floodlights in November. For years photographers have had to cope with awful lights there. Weak and badly positioned, they were far too high, which meant the light just hit the players on the top of their heads often meaning nothing but shadow in the faces. In the second half of the game it started to bucket down. It was very hard to work in the deluge but the new lights being lower and stronger seemed to backlight the raindrops, adding to the atmosphere in this picture</span> </figcaption> </figure>","headline":"Tom Jenkins’s best sports photos of 2014 – in pictures","trailText":"Guardian and Observer staff photographer Tom Jenkins selects his best images from 2014 and recalls in detail how each one was created","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/31/1420022852256/6437df56-aa06-431c-a5a0-d35949816c5f-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"2016","commentable":"true","byline":"Tom Jenkins","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2015-01-03T10:45:00+00:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/gallery/2014/dec/31/tom-jenkins-best-sports-photos-of-2014-in-pictures","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/gallery/2014/dec/31/tom-jenkins-best-sports-photos-of-2014-in-pictures","tags":[{"id":"sport/sport","webTitle":"Sport","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/sport","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/sport","references":[]},{"id":"sport/rugby-union","webTitle":"Rugby union","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/rugby-union","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/rugby-union","references":[]},{"id":"sport/england-rugby-union-team","webTitle":"England rugby union team","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/england-rugby-union-team","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/england-rugby-union-team","references":[]},{"id":"sport/horse-racing","webTitle":"Horse racing","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","section